---

<CoursePage
  title="beyond the scoreboard"
  theme="scoreboard"
  identityLabel="film room // history in play"
  tagline="american history through sports. the games were never just games."
  intro="Sports are never sealed off from the rest of the country. Money, television, law, race, protest, labor, and politics all walk onto the field with the players. We start with the games, then follow whatever they reveal about America. The class ends close to home with a Michigan sports story you choose."
  units={units}
  resources={resources}
>
  <QuickTake
    slot="hook"
    id="scoreboard-opening-take"
    eyebrow="make the call before the replay."
    question="What moves American sports history fastest?"
    options={[
      { label: 'the athletes', response: 'Talent gets attention. Protest and star power can turn that attention into pressure.' },
      { label: 'money + media', response: 'Follow the rights fees, sponsors, and cameras. They explain more of the modern game than most box scores do.' },
      { label: 'law + rules', response: 'A few lines in a law or rulebook can redraw the entire field. Title IX did it in thirty-seven words.' },
    ]}
  />

  <DailyDesk note="history, but with a scoreboard.">
    <TodayCard label="this day in sports" events={sportsEvents} />
    <DailyCard label="the stat that tells a story" entries={stats} />
    <DailyCard label="the rulebook remembers" entries={rules} />
    <DailyCard label="argue this" entries={argueThis} />
  </DailyDesk>
</CoursePage>
